\begin_layout Section
Probability Distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
One Random Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which may assume any 
\emph on
state
\emph default
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{1},x_{2}\cdots x_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 with probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p(x_{1}),p(x_{2})\cdots p(x_{n})\}$
\end_inset

.
 The sum of these probabilities would be 1, since the outcome set is exhaustive.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}p(x_{i})=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider a coin toss event.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 be the result.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\{\mbox{Heads},\mbox{Tails}\}$
\end_inset

.
 For mathematical reasons, it is often desirable to talk in terms of numbers,
 thus we try to denote the outcome by a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the number of heads in one coin toss, so that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\in\{1,0\}\mbox{ corresponds to }\omega\in\{\mbox{Heads},\mbox{Tails}\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a general (fair/unfair) coin toss event, if the probability of heads
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, then the probability of tails is 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\{1,0\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(X)\in\{p,1-p\}$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(X)$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(X)=p^{X}(1-p)^{1-X}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This probability function is called the 
\emph on
probability mass function
\series bold
\emph default
 
\series default
in the case of 
\emph on
discrete
\emph default
 random variables, i.e.
 the outcomes are distinct and form a countable set.
 In the case of 
\emph on
continuous
\emph default
 random variables, where the random variable's outcome set is a range of
 values, this function is called the 
\emph on
probability distribution function
\emph default
.
 As usual, these hold -
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{X=a}^{X=b}p(X)dx=1\mbox{, \ensuremath{X} is continuous, \ensuremath{a\leq X\leq b}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{X=a}^{X=b}p(X)=1\mbox{, \ensuremath{X} is discrete, \ensuremath{a\leq X\leq b}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Two Random Variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When two random variables are considered, then the PMF or PDF form a 3D
 plot with 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y,p(X,Y)$
\end_inset

 along the axes.
 In these cases, the relation relating two dependent variables holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(X=x,Y=y)=p(X=x)\cdot p(Y=y\mbox{ given }X=x)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Obviously, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are independent, then the relation boils down to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(X=x,Y=y)=p(X=x)\cdot p(Y=y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Types of Distributions on the basis of Probability Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Marginal distributions
\emph default
 have one variable, and have probability functions like 
\begin_inset Formula $p(X)$
\end_inset

.

\series bold
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Joint distributions
\emph default
 signify the relation between mutiple variables, and have probability functions
 like 
\begin_inset Formula $p(X,Y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The third type of distributions are called 
\emph on
conditional distributions
\emph default
, and these have probability functions like 
\begin_inset Formula $p(X\mbox{ given }Y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, these concepts may be extended to more than 2 variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conversion Rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To convert probability functions from those of a joint distribution to a
 marginal distribution, we sum over all possible values of other variables.
 For example, if we have two random variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\in\{1,2,3,4,5\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y\in\{6,7,8,9,10\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and we are given 
\begin_inset Formula $p(X,Y)$
\end_inset

, then to find 
\begin_inset Formula $p(X)$
\end_inset

 alone, we can do
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(X)=\sum_{y\in Y}p(X,Y=y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of continuous variables,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(X)=\int_{y\in Y}p(X,Y=y)dy
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

