\begin_layout Section
Moments and their Applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will consider moments only till certain statistical features of distributions.
 In the following discussions, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a positive integer, and 
\begin_inset Formula $E[\cdots]$
\end_inset

 denotes the expectation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Raw Moments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are also called 
\emph on
moments about origin
\emph default
.
 Raw moments of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 are defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{r}'=E[X^{r}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Central Moments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are also called the 
\emph on
moments about the statistical mean
\emph default
, which, as we'll use later, is 
\begin_inset Formula $E[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, central moments of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 are defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{r}=E[(X-E[X])^{r}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Calculations for 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mu_{1}' & = & E[X]=\mbox{statistical mean}\\
\mu_{1} & = & E[(X-E[X])]\\
 & = & E[X]-E[E[X]]\\
 & = & E[X]-E[X]\cdot E[1]\\
 & = & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mu_{2}' & = & E[X^{2}]\\
\mu_{2} & = & E[(X-E[X])^{2}]\\
 & = & E[X^{2}-2\cdot X\cdot E[X]+E[X]^{2}]\\
 & = & E[X^{2}]-2E[X\cdot E[X]]+E[E[X]^{2}]\\
 & = & E[X^{2}]-2E[X]\cdot E[X]+E[X]^{2}\cdot E[1]\\
 & = & E[X^{2}]-E[X]^{2}=\mbox{var(\ensuremath{X})}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Skewness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally saying, 
\emph on
skewness
\emph default
 is the lack of symmetry.
 In symmetric distributions, the mean, median and the mode are equal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
