	filename img/drawing-2.svg
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Pearson's Coefficient of Skewness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a measure of skewness, defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mbox{mean}-\mbox{mode}}{\mbox{standard deviation}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the mode is not well defined, then we use a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 for skewness, which is defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{1}=\frac{\mu_{3}^{2}}{\mu_{2}^{3}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is still an issue with this.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{2}$
\end_inset

, which we proved earlier to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{var(\ensuremath{X})}$
\end_inset

 is always positive, and the numerator is also always positive (due to squaring)
, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 is always positive.
 But skewness can be negative as well.
 Hence, a better measure of skewness is 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

, defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{1}=\sqrt{\beta_{1}}=\frac{\mu_{3}}{\mu_{2}^{3/2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be both positive and negative, depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{3}>0$
\end_inset

, the distribution is positively skewed, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{3}<0$
\end_inset

 says that the distribution is negatively skewed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Kurtosis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Kurtosis refers to the 
\emph on
steepness
\emph default
 of a probability distribution.
 It is measured by 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}$
\end_inset

, defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{2}=\frac{\mu_{4}}{\mu_{2}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}$
\end_inset

 has been, by practice found to be concentrated near 3.
 Thus, a better measure is 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

, defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{2}=\beta_{2}-3
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

