\begin_layout Section
Types of Probability Distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Binomial Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assumptions are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Every trial in a random experiment can result in one of the two possible
 outcomes, which we call 
\emph on
success 
\emph default
and 
\emph on
failure
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Trials are independent, that is, the result of one trial does not affect
 the result of another.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The probability of success is fixed in every trial, say 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the assumptions hold, and there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 trials out of which 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are successes.
 There can be 
\begin_inset Formula $\,^{n}C_{x}$
\end_inset

 such orderings.
 Thus the probability distribution function is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\,^{n}C_{x}\cdot p(\mbox{x successes})=\,^{n}C_{x}\cdot P^{x}(1-P)^{n-x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, notice that these functions form the coefficients of the binomial
 expansion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1^{n}=\{(1-P)+P\}^{n}=\,^{n}C_{0}P^{0}(1-P)^{n}+\,^{n}C_{1}P^{1}(1-P)^{n-1}+\cdots+\,^{n}C_{x}P^{x}(1-P)^{n-x}+\cdots+\,^{n}C_{n}P^{n}(1-P)^{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
moment generating function 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $M_{X}(t)$
\end_inset

 would be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
M_{X}(t) & = & \sum_{x\in X}e^{tx}\cdot p(X=x)\\
 & = & \sum_{x\in X}e^{tx}\cdot\,^{n}C_{x}\cdot P^{x}(1-P)^{n-x}\\
 & = & \sum_{x\in X}\,^{n}C_{x}\cdot(Pe^{t})^{x}(1-P)^{n-x}\\
 &  & \mbox{\ensuremath{X} is a random variable, equal to number of successes, \ensuremath{X=\{0,1,2\cdots n\}}}\\
 &  & \mbox{Assuming \ensuremath{1-P=Q}}\\
M_{X}(t) & = & (Q+Pe^{t})^{n}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some moments are -
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mu_{1}' & = & E[X]\\
 & = & \frac{d}{dt}M_{X}(t)\bigg|_{t=0}\\
 & = & n(Q+Pe^{t})^{n-1}\cdot Pe^{t}\bigg|_{t=0}\\
 & = & n(Q+P)^{n-1}\cdot P\\
 & = & nP\\
\mu_{1} & = & 0\mbox{, as discussed earlier}\\
\mu_{2} & '= & E[X^{2}]\\
 & = & \frac{d^{2}}{dt^{2}}M_{X}(t)\bigg|_{t=0}\\
 & = & nP\cdot\frac{d}{dt}\{(Q+Pe^{t})^{n-1}e^{t}\}\bigg|_{t=0}\\
 & = & nP\cdot\{e^{t}(Q+Pe^{t})^{n-1}+e^{t}(n-1)(Q+Pe^{t})^{n-2}Pe^{t}\}\bigg|_{t=0}\\
 & = & nP\cdot\{(Q+P)^{n-1}+(n-1)(Q+P)^{n-2}P\}\\
 & = & nP\cdot\{1+(n-1)P\}\\
 & = & nP\cdot\{nP+Q\}\\
\mu_{2} & = & \mbox{var(\ensuremath{X})}=E[X^{2}]-E[X]^{2}\\
 & = & nP\cdot(nP+Q)-(nP)^{2}\\
 & = & nPQ
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is interesting to note that statistical mean is greater than variance
 in binomial distributions, since
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
nP>nPQ\mbox{, because \ensuremath{Q=1-P} is less than 1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bernoulli Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bernoulli distribution is a special case of binomial distribution, where
 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Combining Two Binomial Distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us have two binomial distributions, with variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}\sim B(n_{1},P_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}\sim B(n_{2},P_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Then we want to find out when 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}+X_{2}$
\end_inset

 will form a binomial distribution.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 are independent, so the resultant MGF is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
M_{X_{1}+X_{2}}(t) & = & M_{X_{1}}(t)\cdot M_{X_{2}}(t)\\
 & = & (Q_{1}+P_{1}e^{t})^{n_{1}}\cdot(Q_{2}+P_{2}e^{t})^{n_{2}}\\
 & = & (Q+Pe^{t})^{n}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to find if 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1},n_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1},P_{2}$
\end_inset

 can ever give 
\begin_inset Formula $n,P$
\end_inset

 or not, and if yes, then when.
 One trivial possibility is when 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}=P_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}=1-P_{1}=1-P_{2}=Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the MGFs can be combined to give
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{X_{1}+X_{2}}(t)=(Q+Pe^{t})^{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{1}=Q_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P=P_{1}=P_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=n_{1}+n_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Poisson Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a limiting case of binomial distribution.
 It is used to characterise 
\emph on
rare events
\emph default
 (very less 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

) over a very large sample (large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

).
 The assumptions are thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\rightarrow\infty,P\rightarrow0\mbox{ such that }nP=\lambda\mbox{ (some constant)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\bar under
Exercise
\bar default
 : 
\series default
Prove that through some calculations, the 
\emph on
probability mass function
\emph default
 of a poisson distribution can be found out to be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(X=x)=\frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^{x}}{x!}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where x is a non negative integer, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using this value of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(X)$
\end_inset

, the MGF can be found out as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
M_{X}(t) & = & E[e^{tX}]\\
 & = & \sum_{x\in X}e^{tx}\cdot P(X=x)\\
 & = & \sum_{x\in X}e^{tx}\cdot\frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^{x}}{x!}\\
 & = & e^{-\lambda}\sum_{x\in X}\frac{(\lambda e^{t})^{x}}{x!}\\
 & = & e^{-\lambda}\cdot e^{\lambda e^{t}}\\
M_{X}(t) & = & e^{\lambda(e^{t}-1)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some moments are -
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mu_{1}' & = & E[X]\\
 & = & \frac{d}{dt}M_{X}(t)\bigg|_{t=0}\\
 & = & e^{\lambda(e^{t}-1)}\cdot\lambda e^{t}\bigg|_{t=0}\\
 & = & e^{\lambda(1-1)}\cdot\lambda\\
 & = & \lambda\\
\mu_{1} & = & 0\mbox{, as discussed already}\\
\mu_{2}' & = & E[X^{2}]\\
 & = & \frac{d^{2}}{dt^{2}}M_{X}(t)\bigg|_{t=0}\\
 & = & \lambda\cdot\frac{d}{dt}e^{\lambda(e^{t}-1)+t}\bigg|_{t=0}\\
 & = & \lambda e^{\lambda(e^{t}-1)+t}\cdot(\lambda e^{t}+1)\bigg|_{t=0}\\
 & = & \lambda\cdot(\lambda+1)\\
\mu_{2} & = & \mbox{var(\ensuremath{X})}\\
 & = & E[X^{2}]-E[X]^{2}\\
 & = & \lambda\cdot(\lambda+1)-\lambda^{2}\\
 & = & \lambda
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, in a poisson distribution, the statistical mean and the variance are
 equal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
