\begin_layout Subsection
What is estimation?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Estimation is the process of making an intelligent guess about the parameter
 using a statistic.
 The statistic involved in the process is called an 
\emph on
estimator
\emph default
 and its value for a particular sample is called the 
\emph on
estimate
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of a Good Estimator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
unbiasedness
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $E[t]=\theta$
\end_inset

, then the statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\emph on
unbiased
\emph default
 estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 For example, statistical mean is, by definition, an unbiased estimator.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
consistency
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
consistent
\emph default
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\theta$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow N$
\end_inset

, or size of the sample increases to a large value (near the size of the
 population).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
efficiency
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
If there are two estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 is called more 
\emph on
efficient 
\emph default
than 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{var(\ensuremath{t_{1}})\ensuremath{<}var(\ensuremath{t_{2}})}$
\end_inset

.
 A lesser variance indicates a more stable value.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
sufficiency
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
An estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is called 
\emph on
sufficient
\emph default
 for estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 if it utilises all information about 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 available for the sample.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\emph on
hypothesis 
\emph default
is a statement which has not yet been proved.
 A 
\emph on
statistical hypothesis
\emph default
 is a statement about a population which we are trying to prove, through
 a sample.
 Statistical hypotheses can be 
\emph on
parametric 
\emph default
or 
\emph on
non parametric
\emph default
.
 Parametric hypotheses involve parameters of the population.
 Non parametric hypotheses are general statements about a population and
 are not concerned about parameters.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually, for tests, we start with the 
\emph on
null hypothesis
\emph default
 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset


\emph default
.
 In it, we assume equality of conditions.
 For example, if our test is about the success of a new medicine in market,
 we assume in 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 that it will fail.
 The hypothesis against which the null hypothesis is tested is called the
 
\emph on
alternative hypothesis
\emph default
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 So, in the previous example, in 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 we say that the medicine will succeed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Errors Associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0},H_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Type I Error
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
This happens when we reject a null hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 but in actuality, it is true.
 The probability of its occurrence is called the 
\emph on
producer's risk
\emph default
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Type II Error
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
This happens when we accept a false null hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The probability of its occurrence is called 
\emph on
consumer's risk 
\emph default
or 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\emph on
power of the test 
\emph default
is signified by 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\beta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Typically, the sample distribution has a region in which it satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

, called the 
\series bold
acceptance region
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 both depend on the size of the acceptance region, and its location.
 Since it is not possible to minimise both 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 simultaneously, thus we fix one of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 and minimise the other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Test of Significance & Its Relation to Testing of Hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By 
\emph on
test of significance
\emph default
, we mean a statistical test which is used to test the significance of the
 difference between what is assumed in the population, and what is observed
 in the sample.
 What is practically called the test of significance is called the 
\emph on
test of hypothesis
\emph default
 in theory.
 The analogy between the two can be explained as follows.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a random sample 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\{x_{1},x_{2}\cdots x_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider it as an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional point in the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional space composed of all possible such points (or such samples).
 Now divide the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional space into two parts - 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
acceptance region (AR)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
rejection region
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
critical region 
\emph default
(CR)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and see what region the point 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 falls into.
 If it falls into the acceptance region, it supports 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 and otherwise it rejects 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the size of the CR is fixed, practically we are actually fixing 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Further fixing the location of CR decides the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 practically.
 For a given sample size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, it is not possible to simultaneously reduce 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is fixed at a tolerable low level, say 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

, and corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is minimised.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
