\begin_layout Subsection
Test of Single Proportion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we wish to determine if the given coin is fair, and we are provided
 the heads ratio for every few tosses.
 A fair coin would mean that the heads ratio is always typically around
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 So,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p=P_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq P_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:$
\end_inset

 fixed at 
\begin_inset Formula $5\%$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our test statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z=\frac{X-nP_{0}}{\sqrt{nP_{0}Q_{0}}}\sim N(0,1)\mbox{, provided \ensuremath{H_{0}} holds, i.e. \ensuremath{p=P_{0}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq30$
\end_inset

, if we want our statistic to behave like a standard normal variant (normal
 distributions have large sample size).
 Using the previous definite integrals (in normal distributions),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
CR: 
\begin_inset Formula $|Z|\geq1.96$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is because at 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\geq1.96$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\leq-1.96$
\end_inset

 we get two regions which sum to give a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $0.025+0.025=0.05=5\%$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Also note that 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\alpha$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\emph on
confidence
\emph default
.
 Actually, through this CR we say that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(|Z|\geq1.96\mbox{ given that \ensuremath{H_{0}} holds})=5\%
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the coin toss example,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family typewriter
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z=\frac{X-0.5n}{\sqrt{n\times0.5\times0.5}}=\frac{2X-n}{\sqrt{n}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, if we want to test a hypothesis which says that the probability
 of non smokers in a population is greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

, then our hypotheses would be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.1\mbox{, \ensuremath{p} is the probability of finding a non smoker}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p>0.1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The test statistic can be similarly found out.
 But there is a significant difference between this example and the coin
 toss example.
 The coin toss example looked for critical regions, on both sides of the
 distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\neq P_{0}\implies p>P_{0}\mbox{ and }p<P_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus such tests are called 
\emph on
two-tail tests
\emph default
.
 However, in the smokers example, we wanted a greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

 region only, so we are looking on one side of the normal distribution.
 Thus such a test is also called 
\emph on
one-tail test
